1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This constitutes the Schmidt Variation of the Scotch. } 5. Nxc6
{ Now we are in the subvariation called the Mieses Variation. Play will generally revolve around how both players deal with the attack and defense of the White e-pawn. Unusual pawn structures and tactical aspects make this opening one in which the more familiar player tends to have a significant practical advantage. The richness of ideas makes this one of my favorite lines to play from either side ! The Scotch Four Knights Variation after 5. Nc3 is a viable alternative for those looking for options. }
5... bxc6
{ Recapturing with the d-pawn is just positionally bad. White will trade queens and have an endgame pawn structure advantage, an exposed Black king to target, and easy development of his pieces. }
6. e5 { White defends his pawn by advancing it. } 6... Qe7
{ Black judges that the advanced e-pawn may be a weakness rather than a strength and begins to target it. Both players will end up with king bishops that are inconveniently blocked in after White's best response. }
7. Qe2
{ With this move, White forces Black to spend a tempo saving his knight. } 7...
Nd5 { Centralizing is the correct response by Black. } 8. c4
{ White seeks to gain time against the Black knight again along with grabbing space and placing a bid for the d5 square. Black will often want to free his position by playing d5 and this begins to deal with that break. }
8... Ba6
{ Black develops another piece. We will see his other main option of 8... Nb6 in a separate chapter. }
9. b3
{ A significant commitment by White. Alternatives are available here, but playing b3 simplifies the general theme of White's game. He will be able to defend the e-pawn with Bb2 and queen checks from b4 lose most of their sting with the b-pawn protected by the a-pawn instead of the bishop or queen. Moreover, the bishop on a6 often ends up locked out and requiring time to reposition it back into the game. The downside is that black can sometimes send his a-pawn down the board to pry open White's position. }
9... O-O-O
{ Black commits early to castling long and White must be aware of the dangers from the rook operating on the center files. }
10. Bb2
{ g3 is an alternative if our readers find the immediate Bb2 not to their liking. b2 is a very natural square for the bishop and we see no reason not to put it there immediately. }
10... f6 11. Qe4
{ Qe4 is a thematic response to f6, as it breaks the pin on the c-file and forces the Nd5 to move. }
11... Nb6 12. Nd2 fxe5 13. O-O-O
{ Each of White's pieces is better placed than its Black counterpart giving White compensation for the pawn. Additionally, in most lines White will quickly be winning back the e5 pawn and maintaining the better pieces and pawn structure. }
