{ Now we are in the subvariation called the Mieses Variation. Play will generally revolve around how both players deal with the attack and defense of the White e-pawn. Unusual pawn structures and tactical aspects make this opening one in which the more familiar player tends to have a significant practical advantage. The richness of ideas makes this one of my favorite lines to play from either side ! The Scotch Four Knights Variation after 5. Nc3 is a viable alternative for those looking for options. }
5... bxc6
{ Recapturing with the d-pawn is just positionally bad. White will trade queens and have an endgame pawn structure advantage, an exposed Black king to target, and easy development of his pieces. }
6. e5 { White defends his pawn by advancing it. } 6... Qe7
{ Black judges that the advanced e-pawn may be a weakness rather than a strength and begins to target it. Both players will end up with king bishops that are inconveniently blocked in after White's best response. }
7. Qe2
{ With this move, White forces Black to spend a tempo saving his knight. } 7...
Nd5 { Centralizing is the correct response by Black. } 8. c4
{ White seeks to gain time against the Black knight again along with grabbing space and placing a bid for the d5 square. Black will often want to free his position by playing d5 and this begins to deal with that break. }
8... Ba6
{ Black develops another piece. We will see his other main option of 8... Nb6 in a separate chapter. }
9. b3
{ A significant commitment by White. Alternatives are available here, but playing b3 simplifies the general theme of White's game. He will be able to defend the e-pawn with Bb2 and queen checks from b4 lose most of their sting with the b-pawn protected by the a-pawn instead of the bishop or queen. Moreover, the bishop on a6 often ends up locked out and requiring time to reposition it back into the game. The downside is that black can sometimes send his a-pawn down the board to pry open White's position. }
9... g6
{ Reasonably considered the main line, but there are several alternative tries by Black which we will consider. Black has inconvenienced his dark square bishop with Qe7 and now seeks to develop it with thematic purpose, attacking the pesky e-pawn. }
10. Bb2
{ A natural development of the White dark-square bishop. f4 is a viable alternative for those that wish to avoid the upcoming endgame that will be discussed. This also has the advantage of relatively few solid branches from which Black can choose, thus his preparation requirement is simpler. }
10... Bg7
{ Nearly always played. Black continues his intention with g6 of attacking the e-pawn. }
11. g3
{ White needs to solve his light-square bishop development issue as well. From g2, it will help fight for that important d5 square and provide an option to castle. }
11... O-O
{ Black continues to develop. Castling prepares for a rook to get on the e-file and add more pressure to the e-pawn. Black can castle in either direction, but castling short is more common when g6 instead of g5 has been played. }
12. Bg2
{ Completing the idea that started with g3. White really needs to get castled and this opens the path. }
12... Rae8
{ Given the xray attack on the rook on a8 by the bishop on g2, this is the better rook to place on the e-file if Black intends to go for the endgame. }
13. O-O { This is essentially forced. } 13... Bxe5
{ Black goes for a highly debated endgame. } 14. Qxe5
{ The most forcing capture. } 14... Qxe5 { Forced. } 15. Bxe5 { Forced. } 15...
Rxe5 { Forced. } 16. cxd5 { This is the best move here. } 16... Bxf1
{ Forced. } 17. Kxf1
{ Keeping the bishop on a more active square and centralizing the king is the best recapture. }
17... cxd5 { Forced. } 18. Nc3
{ Note, if Black had played Rfe8 on move 12, instead of Rae8, then f4 would be stronger than Nc3 as Black either has to abandon the e-file or the d-pawn. }
18... c6
{ Keeping the pawns together is his best try. We will call this the key endgame position. It is quite complex and while some computers slightly prefer the Black position, reality finds that White scores quite well. Our opinion is that the position gives the better player excellent chances of winning, but, with accurate play from both sides, victory may be quite the challenge. This position is so important and critical to our recommendation, that we think it is worth verbalizing some of the salient points. Let's start with Black's pluses. Looking at material only, Black has a rook and two pawns for the two minor pieces. In general, if the rooks can find open files to use, this will make them very effective. Black also has a passed pawn  (s)  on the d-file. The e-file is his for now, so he has at least one excellent file to work with his rooks. Last, the Black king can get to the central battlefield more easily than the White king can. Now let's look at White's pluses. The e-file is in use for Black, but he has no penetration points. White can essentially force his knight to the c5 square which may compel Black into a somewhat defensive position. Black has more pawn islands and one of his extra pawns is a doubled pawn so he has more weaknesses to worry about. The pieces tend to find working around pass masses easier if the files remain predominantly closed. White's plan will depend on Black's play, but in general, he will look at the following ideas going forward. Na4 eyeing the c5 square when both d6 or d4 are mistakes. If the knight gets to c5, then d6 pushes him to an effective blockading square on d3 and Rc1 targets the new weakness at c6. The bishop usually goes to f3 preventing rook penetration to e2 if Black doubles rooks. The rook will normally go to c1 immobilizing the Black pawns or sometimes d1 with similar intent. As long as the Black rooks only have one file to work with, White should usually refrain from trading a set of rooks unless additional tactical concession is achieved  (Black's rooks tend to get in each other's way when there is only one file for them)  . f4 is sometimes played, but the usual response by Black is Re3 and Rd3 when Black now essentially has two files with which to work so consider this closely before ever playing f4. In the end, we see a lot of ways for White to fight for a win while Black does not have any obvious paths to make any progress. We find the endgame quite pleasant for White and fully worthy of recommendation; however, those that find the endgame not to their liking should look to 10. f4 as an alternative. As far as computer assessments, White can take comfort that this is exactly the kind of endgame that is very difficult for computers  (and humans)  to properly assess and that despite the e-file, extra passed pawn, and king accessibility to the center, they still find White has compensation from a material count only standpoint. }
19. Na4
{ This is our recommendation for White. Alternatively, Rd1, with intention to lift to d4 and then a4 targeting the weak a-pawn, has been tried with some success. }
