9... Qe6
{ Here, Black moves to allow the dark-squared bishop to enter the game. This is the most common move. However, there are a few common alternatives. }
10. Bd2
{ The most common move here is Qe4 when Black has a variety of reasonable responses. After g6 or d5, I believe Black is very close to equal and moreover the queens are likely to come off the board in the d5 line which I think diminishes any advantage White may have in this line. Combined with that and the need to be prepared for multiple lines, I have chosen to simply develop logically  (defending from the most common intended square for the Black bishop)   b4  , and be more familiar in an alternative line that Black is less likely to know and is just as effective given some novelties I have developed in the line. White may still end up playing Qe4, but depending on how Black responds, castling long may be an option and an immediate d5 is not quite as effective with White ready to castle and Black not. Moreover, if Black trades queens after exd en passant, White will be up a tempo in development versus the immediate Qe4 line. At any rate, consider the recommendation 10. Bd2 and proceed with it or the Qe4 as you like. }
10... Ba6
{ Generally considered the strongest line for Black. Pressuring the c-pawn and strengthening d-pawn pushes as well as possibly castling long. On the downside, we are now back into lines with the bishop on a6 which may become misplaced later in the game and require rerouting. }
