{ This is the best way to defend the c-pawn. Weakness on the dark squares is a concern, but I believe White's resources are sufficient if he plays the position prepared. }
11... Ba3
{ Preventing O-O-O and preparing to castle. This is a solid choice for Black. }
12. Qe4
{ Now that Black has committed his bishop to a6, we are more willing to make this commitment. White is structurally fine, playing in the center, and well positioned for a favorable ending if Black elects to simplify. The position is dynamically balanced and the more familiar player should have pragmatic chances. }
12... Qg6
{ This has been suggested as a way to play for a draw by repetition in Dembo and Palliser's excellent book 'The Scotch Game' with Qf3 Qe6 Qe4 Qg6. However, I believe White can improve. }
13. f4 Qxe4+ { Other moves are weaker. } 14. Nxe4 { Forced. } 14... d5 15. exd6
cxd6 16. c5
{ A thematic tactic in many Scotch lines when the bishop is on a6. } 16... Bxf1
17. Nxd6+ Ke7 18. Kxf1 Bxc5 19. Ne4 Ba3 20. Kf2
{ White is doing fine with the superior structure and no problems at all in the position. }
