1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Qh4
{ This move constitutes the Steinitz variation. It applies immediate pressure on the e pawn and represents an aggressive approach from Black. Black's aggression in the form of pressure against the e-pawn, or, if circumstances permit, an attack on the White king. }
5. Nc3
{ Defending the e-pawn without blocking the c1 bishop in. Black's most common next move is quite logical, can you guess it ? }
5... Bb4
{ Of course. This renews the threat to the e-pawn. Other moves are much less common, but we will touch on a couple of them briefly. }
6. Be2
{ With this move, White gambits the e-pawn. It is considered the strongest reply in theory. What does White get for the pawn ? A development advantage and an exposed Black king in most variations. With the offer of the e-pawn, White tries to direct Black's aggression into his choice of Black's plans by encouraging Black to play for winning a pawn and denying attacks on an exposed White king  (as he will be castling soon)  . }
6... Qxe4
{ The pawn is usually accepted and the knight on d4 is attacked twice thus white cannot castle immediately and must save his knight. The standard way of dealing with a gambit where the opponent has a development advantage is to trade pieces and often to give back the pawn for a comfortable position. The biggest issues for Black with accepting the pawn are that he cannot trade a lot of pieces off and he has no easy way to bail out by just giving the pawn back. He will generally end up trading a bishop for knight, have one or both rooks sitting at home unused, and have an exposed king. The biggest issue with not accepting the pawn is that his other plan  (attacking the king)  is simply not justified with no other pieces significantly involved yet. Thus, I deem the early queen move to be objectively inferior versus other choices available to Black. However, it is a dangerous move for an unprepared White player to face. }
7. Nb5
{ Certainly not Nxc6 as the trading of pieces when you have a development advantage dissolves said advantage. With this move, the knight is saved and creates a threat of Nxc7. }
7... Bxc3+
{ Black needs to remove some developed pieces and to do so now either gets the knight to retreat with Nxc3 or ruins White's pawn structure on the queenside with bxc3. We will cover some common alternative errors here. }
8. bxc3
{ Down a pawn, White must focus on dynamic attacking. Static elements such as pawn structure or secondary in this line. Keeping the Nxc7+ threat and having the b-file open for the rook are the path forward. }
8... Kd8
{ Black needs to prevent Nxc7+. Consider why black does not play Qe5 or Qxg2. }
9. O-O
{ Without an immediate tactical blow, the best way to nurture a development advantage is to continue to develop new pieces. Castling protects the g-pawn, but, more importantly, releases the bishop on e2 and creates serious threats related to the rook showing up on the e-file. After this move, we see Black usually try one of three ways to continue forward. }
9... Nge7 { The other knight move is also inadequate. } 10. Re1
{ Again developing more pieces and creating the discovery against the queen. }
10... Qh4
{ A less exposed location for the queen, but one that leaves the squares around Black's king more vulnerable. }
11. Rb1
{ Black really needs to get d6 in to free his position, but with this waiting move that also brings one more piece to the fray, d6 will actually be a mistake that most will make. However, in this line it is already too late for anything much better. If Black avoids the d6 mistake then Rb1 proves its worth even more. Aimed at the b7 square the Rook with team uip with lour Bishop once it moves to f3 to create a lot of pressure on the queenside. Note that a3 by Black will be met at anytime by Nd5 and the Knight trade will further strengthen the Rb1/ Bf3 ideas. }
11... d6 { Trying to get his pieces out. } 12. Nxd6
{ An all too common motif available to White. Watch for this sacrifice possibility often in the Steinitz. }
12... cxd6 { There's nothing better. } 13. Qxd6+ Ke8 14. Bf3 *

